        </div>

        <h2 id="data-migration-setup">Data Migration and Initial Setup (Weeks 2-3)</h2>

        <p>
          Data migration kills more CRM implementations than any other factor. The key is prioritizing the 20% of data that drives 80% of your operations.
        </p>

        <h3>Migration Priority Framework</h3>

        <p>
          <strong>Phase 1 (Week 2):</strong> Core customer data
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Customer contact information (name, address, phone, email)</li>
          <li>Active service contracts and maintenance agreements</li>
          <li>Equipment information for recurring customers</li>
          <li>Payment terms and preferred contact methods</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          <strong>Phase 2 (Week 3):</strong> Historical context
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Service history from past 24 months (older data has minimal operational value)</li>
          <li>Outstanding invoices and payment history</li>
          <li>Technician notes and customer preferences</li>
          <li>Recurring service schedules</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Data Cleaning Best Practices</h3>

        <p>
          Clean your data before migration, not after. Expect to spend 2-3 hours per 1,000 customer records on cleaning activities:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>Standardize address formats (use USPS standards)</li>
          <li>Consolidate duplicate customer records (average reduction: 12-18%)</li>
          <li>Verify phone numbers and email addresses</li>
          <li>Remove customers with no activity in 36+ months</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          Companies that invest in data cleaning report 28% fewer support tickets during the first 90 days of CRM usage.
        </p>

        <h3>Technical Setup Checklist</h3>

        <p>
          Configure these core settings during week 2:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>User accounts and permission levels for all team members</li>
          <li>Service categories and pricing templates</li>
          <li>Automated workflow triggers (appointment reminders, follow-ups)</li>
          <li>Integration with existing tools (accounting software, phone systems)</li>
          <li>Mobile app setup and field testing with 2-3 technicians</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="team-training-onboarding">Team Training and Onboarding (Week 3-4)</h2>

        <p>
          Successful CRM adoption requires hands-on training with real scenarios, not generic software walkthroughs. Companies using job-specific training scenarios achieve 76% higher long-term adoption rates.
        </p>

        <h3>Training Schedule by Role</h3>

        <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
