              <td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Management</td>
              <td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Reporting, performance tracking, system administration</td>
              <td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">3 hours</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>Technician Training Script</h3>

        <p>
          Use this proven 90-minute training sequence for field technicians:
        </p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Minutes 1-15:</strong> App download and login process using their actual credentials</li>
          <li><strong>Minutes 16-45:</strong> Complete a mock service call from arrival to payment collection</li>
          <li><strong>Minutes 46-70:</strong> Practice common scenarios (parts ordering, customer communication, photo uploads)</li>
          <li><strong>Minutes 71-90:</strong> Troubleshooting common issues and Q&A session</li>
        </ol>

        <p>
          The key is using real job scenarios, not generic examples. Technicians trained on actual customer data show 43% faster adoption rates.
        </p>

        <h3>Creating System Champions</h3>

        <p>
          Identify 1-2 early adopters per department to serve as peer trainers. These champions should:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>Receive advanced training 1 week before general rollout</li>
          <li>Complete 5-10 real jobs using the new system before training others</li>
          <li>Lead peer training sessions within their departments</li>
          <li>Serve as first-line support for basic questions</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          Companies using peer champions report 67% fewer support tickets and 23% higher user satisfaction scores.
        </p>

        <h2 id="first-30-days-roadmap">Your First 30 Days Roadmap</h2>

        <p>
          The first month determines long-term success. Companies that hit these specific milestones have a 91% chance of successful long-term adoption.
        </p>

        <h3>Week 1: Soft Launch</h3>

        <p>
          Run parallel systems with 20% of your daily operations:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>Process 3-5 service calls entirely through the new CRM</li>
          <li>Schedule maintenance appointments for the following week</li>
          <li>Generate and send 2-3 invoices through the system</li>
          <li>Train one additional team member daily</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          Track time-to-completion for key tasks. Initial slowdown of 15-25% is normal during week 1.
        </p>

        <h3>Week 2: Expand Usage</h3>

        <p>
          Increase to 50% of operations while maintaining parallel tracking:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>All new customer interactions go through the CRM</li>
          <li>Begin using mobile features for field operations</li>
          <li>Start automated customer communications (confirmations, reminders)</li>
          <li>Generate first weekly performance report</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Week 3: Full Deployment</h3>

        <p>
          Process 80% of operations through the CRM:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>Eliminate paper-based processes except for emergency backup</li>
          <li>Require mobile app usage for all field technicians</li>
          <li>Begin customer payment processing through the system</li>
          <li>Start measuring efficiency improvements</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Week 4: Optimization</h3>

        <p>
          Fine-tune processes based on real usage data:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>Adjust automated workflows based on user feedback</li>
          <li>Optimize mobile app settings for field conditions</li>
          <li>Configure advanced reporting for management review</li>
          <li>Plan month 2 feature rollout (advanced scheduling, inventory management)</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="measuring-success">Measuring Implementation Success</h2>

        <p>
          Track these specific metrics to validate your implementation investment and identify improvement opportunities.
        </p>

        <h3>30-Day Success Metrics</h3>

        <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
